# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-overview
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:azure-overview/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A **data center** is a facility used to house computer systems and associated components, such as telecommunications and storage systems.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data centers are critical infrastructure for the storage and processing of information, and they support the global financial system, cloud services, machine learning, and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data centers vary widely in terms of size, power and water requirements, and overall structure.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Hyperscale and colocation facilities collectively account for approximately 74% of U.S. server energy consumption as of 2023, a share that has grown significantly over the past decade as workloads have migrated away from enterprise on-premises infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Since IT operations are crucial for business continuity, a data center generally includes redundant or backup components.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Other important design considerations are power supply, network infrastructure, environmental controls (e.g., cooling, fire suppression), and various measures for physical and data security.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Large data centers operate at an industrial scale, requiring significant energy.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Estimated global data center electricity consumption in 2024 was around 415 terawatt hours (TWh), or about 1.5% of global electricity demand.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The International Energy Agency (IEA) projects that data center electricity consumption could double by 2030.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of data center infrastructure has prompted regulatory debates in multiple jurisdictions regarding tax incentives, electricity grid impacts, water consumption, and compatibility with state and national climate commitments.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Rapid growth of the AI industry is leading to strain on electric grids and increased electricity costs for consumers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This in turn has drawn growing opposition to new data centers from local people who would bear the burdens of social and environmental impacts, such as energy and water use, while faraway actors and institutions would receive the projects' benefits.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] These opposition movements have materialized especially in parts of Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Billions of dollars in projects were halted or delayed by data center resistances in the U.S. between May 2024 and June 2025.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data centers are usually classified according to their ownership model, scale, and intended use.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] However, these classifications are not mutually exclusive from each other, and they may overlap depending on the operational structure and service model of the particular data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Enterprise data centers are owned and operated by a single organization for their own internal information technology (IT) needs, rather than for commercial hosting of other companies' data.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] They used to be essential infrastructures; as in 2014, enterprise data centers accounted for over 60% of the U.S. server energy consumption, but this share fell sharply to about 10% by 2023 as workloads migrated to hyperscale and colocation facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Energy efficiency at an enterprise data center tends to be significantly lower than at hyperscale facilities due to its cooling, which can account for over 30% of electricity consumption at enterprise sites, compared to roughly 7% at efficient hyperscale data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The shift away from enterprise facilities toward cloud and colocation infrastructure is one of the defining structural trends of the previous decade.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Colocation centers provide shared physical infrastructure, such as power, cooling, space, etc., to multiple tenants who lease space rather than building their own facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Colocation data centers reduce expenditure for organizations while enabling operators to achieve economies of scale in power procurement and cooling efficiency.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Some of the largest data centers in the world are colocation centers, and this category accounted for about 22% of worldwide data center capacity as of 2024, making them the second-largest category by capacity after hyperscale facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Major colocation providers include Equinix, Switch, COPT, and Digital Realty, which operate facilities across multiple continents.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Hyperscale data centers are large-scale facilities, typically exceeding 100 megawatts of power capacity, designed to support massive, scalable computing workloads for cloud services, AI training, and large-scale data processing.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] By the end of 2024, there were 1,136 operational hyperscale data centers globally, a figure that doubled over the previous five years, with the U.S. accounting for approximately 54% of total hyperscale capacity.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In particular, the three largest operators, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud, collectively account for approximately 59% of all hyperscale data center capacity globally.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As a growing trend, hyperscale data centers represented about 41% of worldwide data center capacity in 2024 and are projected to exceed 60% by 2029 as enterprise on-premises infrastructure continues to decline.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Moreover, as artificial intelligence (AI) is becoming widely used, AI data centers are being built more rapidly, and they can consume as much electricity as 100,000 households, more than conventional data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Since 2024, there has been widespread grassroots Opposition to AI Data Centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Edge data centers are smaller facilities, typically ranging from 1 to 10 megawatts.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] They are positioned closer to end users or data sources to reduce network latency and support real-time applications, such as autonomous vehicles, industrial automation, and content delivery.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Unlike hyperscale data centers, edge data centers are intentionally distributed across many locations rather than consolidated, with deployments occurring in urban areas, cell tower sites, as well as industrial locations.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The growth of edge computing infrastructure has been tied to the expansion of 5G wireless networks and the increasing use of Internet of Things (IoT) devices, which generate data that is more efficiently processed near its source than transmitted to a centralized data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Micro data centers (MDCs) are access-level data centers that are smaller in size than traditional data centers but provide the same features.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] They are typically located near the data source to reduce communication delays, as their small size allows several MDCs to be spread out over a wide area.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] MDCs are suited to user-facing, front end applications.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] They are commonly used in edge computing and other areas where low latency data processing is needed.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Modularity and flexibility are key elements in allowing a data center to grow and change over time.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data center modules are pre-engineered, standardized building blocks that can be configured and moved as needed.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A modular data center may consist of data center equipment contained within shipping containers or similar portable containers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Components of the data center can be prefabricated and standardized, which facilitates moving if needed.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] These modular data centers are useful for IT disaster recovery.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Mobile data centers are also used to move large quantities of data, by physically transporting the hardware that contains it, and in cryptocurrency mining, where fleets of mobile data centers are transported to take advantage of cheaper sources of energy.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data centers have their roots in the huge computer rooms of the 1940s, typified by the Electronic Numerical Integrator and Computer (ENIAC), one of the earliest examples of a data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Early computer systems were complex to operate and maintain, and required a special environment in which to operate.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Many cables were necessary to connect all of the components, and methods to accommodate and organize these were devised such as standard racks to mount equipment, raised floors, and cable trays (installed overhead or under the elevated floor).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A single mainframe required a great deal of power and had to be cooled to avoid overheating.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Security became important – computers were expensive, and were often used for government and military purposes.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As such, basic design guidelines for controlling access to the computer room were devised.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] During the microcomputer industry boom of the 1980s, computers started to be deployed everywhere, in many cases with little or no care about operating requirements.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] However, as information technology (IT) operations started to grow in complexity, organizations grew aware of the need to control IT resources.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The availability of inexpensive networking equipment, coupled with new standards for the network structured cabling, made it possible to use a hierarchical design that put servers in a specific room inside the company.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The use of the term *data center*, as applied to specially designed computer rooms, started to gain popular recognition about this time.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] During the dot-com bubble (1997–2000), there was a boom in data center construction because companies needed fast Internet connectivity and non-stop operation to establish their Internet presence.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The global data center market saw steady growth in the 2010s, with a notable acceleration in the latter half of the decade.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] According to Gartner, worldwide data center infrastructure spending reached $200 billion in 2021, representing a 6% increase from 2020 despite economic challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2024, global energy consumption from data centers was 620 TWh, with 80% of that consumption concentrated in the U.S., China, and the United Kingdom.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Colocation centers were the most common category worldwide, with 4,799 colocation centers in 127 countries.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In that year, the largest data center in the world was Citadel, owned by Switch, at the Tahoe Reno Industrial Center in Reno, Nevada, occupying 7.2 million square feet.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Growth of the data center industry has prompted local resistance.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A 2023 survey found social mobilizations against the industry in Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] These movements expressed concern about the centers' energy and water use, pollution, and impact on agriculture or the landscape.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A 2026 poll by *Politico* suggested that resistance to growth of the industry would make candidates' stance on data centers a significant issue for voters in the U.S.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The U.S. hosted 5,381 data centers in March 2024, the highest number of any country worldwide, accounting for 40% of the global market in 2023.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As of 2023, about 80% of U.S. data center load was concentrated in 15 states, led by Virginia and Texas.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As of 2025, roughly one third of America's data centers were in three states: Virginia (643), Texas (395), and California (319).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The largest concentration of data centers in the world is in Northern Virginia, with over 250 facilities in the region.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2025, Georgia was the fastest growing data center hub in the U.S., having enacted several state tax exemptions for the industry and hosting between 100 and 150 centers in the state.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Local governments have responded to the growing industry in Georgia with a variety of local ordinances to guide permitting of these facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The consultancy firm McKinsey & Co., projected U.S. demand to double to 35 gigawatts (GW) by 2030, up from 17 GW in 2022.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A study published by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) in May 2024 estimated that data centers could consume between 4.6% and 9.1% of the country's electricity generation by 2030.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] GDP growth was only 0.1% without the investments in data centers for artificial intelligence.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data centers house critical computing resources in a controlled environment and must generally operate with very high availability.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Key design elements include providing power for the equipment, temperature and humidity control, cabling, fire safety, and security.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] For this reason, a data center has to offer a secure environment that minimizes the chances of a security breach.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Industry research company International Data Corporation (IDC) puts the average age of a data center at nine years old.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Gartner, another research company, says data centers older than seven years are obsolete.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The growth in data (163 zettabytes by 2025) is one factor driving the need for data centers to modernize.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Rapid obsolescence of data center equipment was a concern by at least 2007, and in 2011, Uptime Institute was concerned about aging equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The topology proposed in this document is intended to be applicable to any size data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Telcordia GR-3160, *NEBS Requirements for Telecommunications Data Center Equipment and Spaces*, provides guidelines for data center spaces within telecommunications networks, and environmental requirements for the equipment intended for installation in those spaces.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] These criteria were developed jointly by Telcordia and industry representatives.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] They may be applied to data center spaces housing data processing or IT equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Power supplies, either back up or continuous onsite power, consist of one or more uninterruptible power supplies, battery banks, diesel, gas turbine, and/or gas engine generating sets.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Greater primary fuel energy efficiency can be achieved with the use of cogeneration technology, generating electricity, heating, and cooling onsite.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] To prevent single points of failure, all elements of the electrical systems, including backup systems, are typically given redundant copies, and critical servers are connected to both the *A-side* and *B-side* power feeds.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This arrangement is often made to achieve N+1 redundancy in the systems.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Static transfer switches are sometimes used to ensure instantaneous switchover from one supply to the other in the event of a power failure.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Options for low-voltage cable routing might include data cabling that is routed through overhead cable trays; raised floor cabling, both for security reasons and to avoid the extra cost of cooling systems over the racks; and anti-static tiles for flooring, especially in low-cost data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Maintaining suitable temperature and humidity levels is critical to preventing equipment damage caused by overheating.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Overheating can cause components (usually the silicon or copper of the wires or circuits) to melt, causing loose connections and fire hazards.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Typical temperature control methods include air conditioning and indirect cooling, such as the use of outside air, indirect evaporative cooling units, and seawater cooling.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Airflow management is the practice of achieving data center cooling efficiency by preventing the recirculation of hot exhaust air and by reducing bypass airflow.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Common approaches include hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment and the deployment of in-row cooling units, which position cooling directly between server racks to intercept exhaust heat before it mixes with room air.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Humidity control prevents moisture and related issues.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] For example, excess humidity can cause dust to adhere more readily to fan blades and heat sinks, impeding air cooling and leading to higher temperatures.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Cold aisle containment is done by exposing the rear of equipment racks, while the fronts of the servers are enclosed with doors and covers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This is similar to how large-scale food companies refrigerate and store products.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Computer cabinets/server farms are often organized for containment of hot/cold aisles.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Proper air duct placement prevents cold and hot air from mixing.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Rows of cabinets are paired to face each other so the cool and hot air intakes and exhausts do not mix air, which would severely reduce cooling efficiency.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Alternatively, a range of underfloor panels can create efficient cold air pathways directed to the raised-floor vented tiles.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Either the cold aisle or the hot aisle can be contained.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Another option is fitting cabinets with vertical exhaust duct chimneys.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Hot exhaust pipes/vents/ducts can direct the air into a plenum space above a dropped ceiling and back to the cooling units or to outside vents.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] With this configuration, traditional hot/cold aisle configuration is not required.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data centers feature fire protection systems, including passive and active design elements, as well as implementation of fire prevention programs in operations.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Smoke detectors are usually installed to provide early warning of a fire.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Although the main room usually does not allow wet pipe-based systems due to the fragile nature of circuit boards, there are systems that can be used in the rest of the facility or in cold/hot aisle air circulation systems that are closed systems.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] These include sprinkler systems and misting, the latter of which uses high pressure to create extremely small water droplets and can be used in sensitive rooms due to the nature of the droplets.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] However, there are other means to put out fires, especially in Sensitive areas, usually using gaseous fire suppression, of which Halon gas was the most popular, until the negative effects of producing and using it were discovered.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Physical access to data centers is usually restricted.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Layered security often starts with fencing, bollards, and mantraps.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Video camera surveillance and permanent security guards are almost always present if the data center is large or contains sensitive information.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Fingerprint recognition is starting to become commonplace.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Logging access is required by some data protection regulations; some organizations tightly link this to access control systems.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Multiple log entries can occur at the main entrance, entrances to internal rooms, and at equipment cabinets.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Access control at cabinets can be integrated with intelligent power distribution units, so locks are networked through the same appliance.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data center transformation takes a step-by-step approach through integrated projects carried out over time.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This differs from a traditional method of data center upgrades, which takes a serial and siloed approach.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Typical projects within a data center transformation initiative include standardization/consolidation, virtualization, automation, and security.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data center consolidation consists of reducing the number of data centers and avoiding *server sprawl* (both physical and virtual), which often includes replacing aging data center equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This process is aided by standardization, which makes these systems follow a uniform set of configurations to simplify and improve efficiency.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Automating tasks such as provisioning, configuration, patching, release management, and compliance are other ways in which data centers can be upgraded.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] These changes are needed not just when facing fewer skilled IT workers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Lastly, security initiatives integrate the protection of virtual systems with existing security for physical infrastructures.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The first raised floor computer room was made by IBM in 1956 to allow access for wiring.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] During the 1970s, raised floors became more common because they allow cool air to circulate more efficiently.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A raised floor standards guide (GR-2930) was developed by Telcordia Technologies, a subsidiary of Ericsson.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The "lights-out" data center, also known as a darkened or dark data center, is a data center that has largely eliminated the need for direct access by personnel, except under extraordinary circumstances.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Due to the lack of need for staff to enter the data center, it can be operated without lighting.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] All of the devices are accessed and managed by remote systems, with automation programs used to perform unattended operations.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In addition to the energy savings, reduction in staffing costs, and the ability to locate the site further from population centers, implementing a lights-out data center also reduces the threat of malicious attacks upon the infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulations require monitoring of noise levels inside data centers if noise exceeds 85 decibels.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The average noise level in server areas of a data center may reach as high as 92–96 dB(A).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Residents living near data centers have described the sound as "a high-pitched whirring noise 24/7", saying "It's like being on a tarmac with an airplane engine running constantly ...
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] External sources of noise include HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning) equipment and energy generators.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Location factors include proximity to power grids, telecommunications infrastructure, networking services, transportation lines, and emergency services.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Other considerations should include flight paths, neighboring power drains, geological risks, and climate (associated with cooling costs).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Local political considerations, such as availability of subsidies and lack of opposition, are also important factors in locating data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Various metrics exist to measure the data-availability that results from data-center availability beyond 95% uptime, with the top of the scale counting how many *nines* can be placed after *99%*.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The costs of avoiding downtime should not exceed the cost of the downtime itself.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Dynamic infrastructure provides the ability to intelligently, automatically, and securely move workloads within a data center anytime, anywhere, for migrations, provisioning, to enhance performance, or build co-location facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] It also facilitates performing routine maintenance on either physical or virtual systems, all while minimizing interruption.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A related concept is Composable Infrastructure, which allows for the dynamic reconfiguration of the available resources to suit needs, only when needed.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Communications in modern data centers are most often based on networks running the Internet protocol suite.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data centers contain a set of routers and switches that transport traffic between the servers and to the outside world, which are connected according to the data center network architecture.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Redundancy of the internet connection is often provided by using two or more upstream service providers (see Multihoming).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Some of the servers at a data center are used for running the basic internet and intranet services needed by internal users in the organization, e.g., e-mail servers, proxy servers, and DNS servers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Network security elements are also usually deployed: firewalls, VPN gateways, intrusion detection systems, and so on.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Also common are monitoring systems for the network and some of the applications.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Additional off-site monitoring systems are also typical, in case of a failure of communications inside the data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Energy consumption and the environmental impacts it creates are a central issue for data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Power draw ranges from a few kilowatts (kW) for small server racks to several tens of megawatts (MW) for large facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Modern hyperscale data centers can exhibit power densities exceeding 100 times those of conventional office buildings, primarily due to the high concentration of servers and cooling systems required to manage continuous digital workloads.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] For higher power density facilities, electricity costs are a dominant operating expense and account for over 10% of the total cost of ownership (TCO) of a data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As of 2024, data centers in the U.S. are primarily powered by natural gas, which supplies 40% of their electricity (with renewable energy at 24%, nuclear at about 20%, and coal at about 15%).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The *Associated Press* reported that electricity for AI data centers in the U.S. would likely come from natural gas or oil, as companies prefer using currently available power plants, which primarily use fossil fuels.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Fossil energy is also often cheaper in locations where data centers are developed, and experts believe that energy demands from generative AI and data centers would be difficult to fulfill with renewable energy alone.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Some companies such as Google, Amazon, and Meta have expressed interest in nuclear power for their data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As of 2020, according to the IEA, solar photovoltaic-generated electricity is at its lowest cost in history.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Other data centers, including xAI's Colossus, OpenAI's Stargate, and Meta's Prometheus use their own off-grid natural gas plants.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Electric vehicle and lithium-ion batteries have also been used for powering data centers, including for Colossus.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Power utility companies make upgrades to their infrastructure to handle demands of new data centers, and the price for these changes typically falls on residential or smaller commercial consumers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2025, the Mountain Valley Pipeline announced plans to expand its capacity by 25% to meet energy needs for data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In December 2025, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) published a unanimous order allowing data centers in the U.S. to have a direct connection with power plants.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] United States Secretary of Energy Chris Wright expressed support for un-retiring coal plants to power AI data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Electricity demands from AI data centers have slowed or reversed the retirement of peaking power plants in the U.S.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] For example, in 2025, Southern Company announced that energy use from data centers would prevent the company from retiring coal-fired power plants as it had earlier promised.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In Nevada, the Desert Research Institute (DRI) calculated that 35% of the state's energy production could go to data centers by the year 2030 if all projects planned in the state as of 2026 are completed.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] DRI also stated, in areas where there are clusters of data centers, local consumers may end up paying the extra cost of expanding infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2024, data centers were estimated to account for about 1.5% of global electricity consumption (approximately 415 TWh) and around 1% of greenhouse gas emissions according to U.S.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] However, the rapid expansion is causing projections to rise sharply.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Due to accelerated demand from AI, data center's global electricity consumption is projected to more than double to around 945 TWh by 2030 in the IEA's base-case scenario, which represents just under 3% of 2030 total global electricity consumption.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This growing electricity demand, much of which is still generated by fossil fuels, increases the potential environmental impacts.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In addition to operational energy demand, embodied life cycle emissions should be considered, which include the extraction, manufacturing, transportation, and recycling or disposal of materials used in the construction of facilities and hardware.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Global data center carbon dioxide emissions are projected to rise from an estimated 220 million tonnes in 2024 to 300–320 million tonnes by 2035.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google and Microsoft each consumed more power than over 100 countries.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As a result, there is increasing industry pressure for decarbonization.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Companies are pursuing direct clean energy agreements, such as Tencent who has pledged to be carbon neutral by 2030, and Microsoft's 2024 agreement to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide 100% of the electric power for its AI data centers for 20 years.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The most commonly used energy efficiency metric for data centers is power usage effectiveness (PUE), calculated as the ratio of total power entering the data center divided by the power used by IT equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] PUE measures the percentage of power used by overhead devices (cooling, lighting, etc.).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The average U.S. data center has a PUE of 2.0, meaning two watts of total power (overhead + IT equipment) for every watt delivered to IT equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] State-of-the-art data centers are estimated to have a PUE of roughly 1.2.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Google publishes quarterly efficiency metrics from its data centers in operation.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] PUEs of as low as 1.01 have been achieved with two-phase immersion cooling.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The EPA has an Energy Star rating for standalone or large data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] To qualify for the ecolabel, a data center must be within the top quartile in energy efficiency of all reported facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The Energy Efficiency Improvement Act of 2015 (U.S.) requires federal facilities—including data centers—to operate more efficiently.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] California's Title 24 (2014) of the California Code of Regulations mandates that every newly constructed data center must have some form of airflow containment in place to optimize energy efficiency.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The European Union (EU) also has a similar initiative: EU Code of Conduct for Data Centres.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Efficiency improvements and renewable energy integration are helping offset some emissions, but fossil fuels remain a major electricity source for data center operations worldwide.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2011, server racks in data centers were designed for more than 25 kW, and the typical server was estimated to waste about 30% of the electricity it consumed.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The energy demand for information storage systems is also rising.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A high-availability data center is estimated to have a 1 MW demand and consume $20 million in electricity over its lifetime, with cooling representing 35% to 45% of the data center's total cost of ownership.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Calculations show that in two years, the cost of powering and cooling a server could be equal to the cost of purchasing the server hardware.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Research in 2018 showed that a substantial amount of energy could still be conserved by optimizing IT refresh rates and increasing server use.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Research for optimizing task scheduling is also underway, with researchers looking to implement energy-efficient scheduling algorithms that could reduce energy consumption by anywhere between 6% and 44%.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2011, Facebook, Rackspace, and others founded the Open Compute Project (OCP) to develop and publish open standards for greener data center computing technologies.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As part of the project, Facebook published the designs of its server, which it had built for its first dedicated data center in Prineville.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Making servers taller left space for more effective heat sinks and enabled the use of fans that moved more air with less energy.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] By not buying commercial off-the-shelf servers, energy consumption due to unnecessary expansion slots on the motherboard and unneeded components, such as a graphics card, was also saved.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2016, Google joined the project and published the designs of its 48V DC shallow data center rack.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This design had long been part of Google data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] By eliminating the multiple transformers usually deployed in data centers, Google had achieved a 30% increase in energy efficiency.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2017, sales for data center hardware built to OCP designs topped $1.2 billion and are expected to reach $6 billion by 2021.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Power is the largest recurring cost to the user of a data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2008, the ASHRAE recommended a temperature range of 64.4 °F (18.0 °C) to 80.6 °F (27.0 °C), though some data centers could operate at higher temperatures.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] However, cooling at or below 70 °F (21 °C) wastes money and energy.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Furthermore, overcooling equipment in environments with a high relative humidity can expose equipment to a high amount of moisture that facilitates the growth of salt deposits on conductive filaments in the circuitry.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A **power and cooling analysis**, also referred to as a thermal assessment, measures the relative temperatures in specific areas as well as the capacity of the cooling systems to handle specific ambient temperatures.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Power cooling density is a measure of how much square footage the center can cool at maximum capacity.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The cooling of data centers is the second largest power consumer after servers, with cooling taking about 7% to 30% of energy usage (depending on efficiency), compared to an average of 60% of energy used by servers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] An energy efficiency analysis measures the energy use of data center IT and facilities equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A typical energy efficiency analysis measures factors such as a data center's Power Use Effectiveness (PUE) against industry standards, identifies mechanical and electrical sources of inefficiency, and identifies air-management metrics.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] However, the limitation of most current metrics and approaches is they do not include IT in the analysis.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Case studies have shown that by addressing energy efficiency holistically in a data center, major efficiencies can be achieved that are not possible otherwise.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Thermal zone mapping uses sensors and computer modeling to create a three-dimensional image of the hot and cool zones in a data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This information can help identify optimal positioning of data center equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] For example, critical servers might be placed in a cool zone that is serviced by redundant AC units.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Data centers use a lot of power, consumed via two main usages: the power required to run the equipment and the power required to cool the equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Power efficiency reduces the first category.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Cooling cost reduction through natural means includes location decisions.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] When the focus is avoiding good fiber connectivity, power grid connections, and people concentrations to manage the equipment, a data center can be miles away from users.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Mass data centers like Google or Facebook do not need to be near population centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Arctic locations that can use outside air, which provides cooling, are becoming more popular.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Countries with favorable conditions, such as Canada, Finland, Sweden, Norway, and Switzerland are trying to attract cloud computing data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Singapore lifted a three-year ban on new data centers in April 2022.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A major data center hub for the Asia-Pacific region, Singapore lifted its moratorium on new data center projects in 2022, granting four new projects, but rejecting more than 16 data center applications from over 20 received.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] It is very difficult to reuse the heat that comes from air-cooled data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] For this reason, data center infrastructures are more often equipped with heat pumps.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of artificial intelligence (AI) and high-performance computing workloads has increased attention on data center power infrastructure, particularly the relationship between electrical reliability, deployment timelines, energy costs, and decarbonization objectives.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Industry publications have described phased approaches to infrastructure development that enable operators to deploy power capacity rapidly while maintaining pathways toward lower-carbon energy systems as technologies, fuel availability, grid capacity, and economics evolve.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Recent industry discussion has also emphasized "speed-to-power" as a significant consideration in data center development, reflecting the growing importance of securing electrical capacity and resilient power systems within increasingly compressed project timelines.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In the 2020s, the rapid growth of data center construction gave rise to policy debates over tax incentives, electricity grid, water resources, and climate commitments.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] By 2024, at least 36 U.S. states had introduced specific tax incentives aimed at attracting data center investment, most often in the form of sales tax exemptions on servers, networking equipment, and electricity.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Virginia hosts the largest concentration of data centers in the U.S., and a December 2024 audit by its Joint Legislative Audit and Review Commission (JLARC) put the industry's annual contribution at roughly 74,000 jobs and $9.1 billion in gross state product.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The audit reported that the state's sales and use tax exemption was claimed by about 90% of operators and that reduced state revenue by an estimated $928 million in fiscal year 2023.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Thus, JLARC concluded that ending the exemption would likely shrink Virginia's share of new data center investment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Economists have debated the effectiveness of such incentives more broadly.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Further, research by Timothy Bartik of the Upjohn Institute estimated that economic development incentives change firm location decisions in only 2% to 25% of cases.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In response to tax exemption policies, several jurisdictions have started to reevaluate incentives for data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2024, the Georgia General Assembly passed legislation to terminate the state's data center sales tax exemption.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] However, the bill was ultimately vetoed by Governor Brian Kemp.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In another case in 2026, the Virginia Senate voted 28 to 12 to phase out the state's data center sales tax exemption as part of broader budget negotiations.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Most large data centers use water for evaporative cooling of their servers, and the volumes involved have drawn growing scrutiny.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A 2021 study in *npj Clean Water* estimated that U.S. data centers directly consume about 1.7 billion liters of water per day, with up to 57% of that drawn from potable supplies, and noted that fewer than one-third of operators measured their water use at the time.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] A separate study published in *Environmental Research Letters* found that about one-fifth of direct water use by U.S. data centers came from moderately or highly water-stressed watersheds, and that nearly half of the country's servers ran on electricity drawn from water-stressed regions.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] According to a 2024 Berkeley Lab report, data centers in the U.S. had used approximately 17 billion gallons of water.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The same report expected hyperscale data centers specifically to use 16 to 33 billion gallons of water per year by 2028.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In Virginia, the December 2024 JLARC audit reported that data centers in the state consumed about 2.1 billion gallons of water in 2023, an 86% increase since 2019, and that roughly one-third of that came from reclaimed water rather than potable supplies.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The audit recommended that local governments be authorized to require water-use estimates as part of the data center permitting process.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] There is no federal U.S. standard requiring data center operators to disclose water consumption, and access to facility-level data has often been limited by non-disclosure agreements (NDAs) with host municipalities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2022, the city of The Dalles, Oregon, settled a public records lawsuit brought by *The Oregonian*, after which Google ended its nationwide practice of treating site-level water use as a trade secret.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2025, several states considered legislation to require data centers to disclose water use, including bills in Virginia, California, and New Jersey, although each was vetoed by the state's governor that year.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The growth of data center electricity demand in the 2020s has prompted regulatory debates over grid capacity, transmission planning, and how the costs of new infrastructure should be allocated among customers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The 2024 Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL) report on U.S. data center energy use, prepared at the request of the U.S.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Congress, estimated that data centers accounted for about 4.4% of national electricity consumption in 2023 and projected a rise to between 6.7% and 12% by 2028, depending on growth scenarios.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2025, the IEA projected that data centers would account for nearly half of new U.S. electricity demand growth through 2030.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), the federally designated electric reliability organization for the U.S., identified data centers as the single largest driver of projected demand growth in its 2024 long-term reliability assessment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Additionally, NERC documented a voltage event in the PJM Interconnection region in July 2024, in which roughly 1,500 megawatts of data center load disconnected simultaneously across about 60 facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] How the costs of meeting this demand are shared has also become a central policy question.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The JLARC audit in 2024 estimated that, without any changes to how rates are designed, typical residential customers of Dominion Energy Virginia could see their bills rise by $14 to $37 per month by 2040 because of data center-driven grid investment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] As such, the report recommended creating a separate customer rate class for large data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Some researchers have urged caution in interpreting demand projections.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Furthermore, a 2024 commentary in the journal *Joule* argued that public estimates of future data center electricity use vary widely and that utilities have historically over-forecasted load growth, and called for more transparent data on actual facility-level consumption.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The growth of data centers has raised questions about whether the renewable energy commitments made by their operators are consistent with broader climate goals.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Many large operators report meeting electricity-related emissions targets through annual purchases of renewable energy certificates (RECs) or matching their total annual consumption with renewable generation.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2022, a study by *Nature Climate Change* analyzed 115 companies with Science Based Targets.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] It found that about 42% of their reported Scope 2 emissions reductions disappeared once REC-based claims were excluded.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] This directly suggests that some corporate climate progress reflected accounting choices rather than actual reductions in grid emissions.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In response, some operators and researchers have proposed 24/7 carbon-free energy matching.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Under this approach, every hour of a facility's electricity use must be matched with carbon-free generation on the same regional grid.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The authors found that annual or volumetric matching did little to cut grid emissions under current U.S. policy.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Hourly 24/7 matching cut more, but it cost about $13 to $30 more per megawatt-hour.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] The tension between data center expansion and corporate climate goals has also become apparent in the operators' own disclosures of information.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google reported its greenhouse gas emissions had risen by about 48% since 2019, attributing the increase in large part to data center electricity use associated with AI workloads.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Similarly, Microsoft reported in 2024 that its emissions had risen by about 29% since 2020, citing the construction and operation of new data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p01] Moreover, the IEA projected in 2025 that global data center carbon dioxide emissions could peak at around 320 million tonnes by 2030 before declining slightly through 2035, with the trajectory depending heavily on the carbon intensity of the electricity supplied to new facilities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Data centers have significant impacts on local ecologies, politics, and utility infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Political and economic incentives such as tax breaks, land deals, or government subsidies drive data center growth in areas where these incentives are available.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Data centers are frequently located in rural areas, where they may displace agriculture.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Growth in the data center industry has prompted several debates about environmental impacts, especially the massive energy and water demands.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] The supply chains, emissions, and e-waste also impose significant planetary impacts, raising questions of environmental injustice toward marginalized communities that frequently bear these burdens.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Multiple studies and experts have found that data centers do not bring high-paying jobs to local communities in proportion to the tax subsidies they receive.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] The rapid expansion of AI data centers has raised significant concerns over their water consumption, particularly in drought-prone regions.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] According to the IEA, a single 100-megawatt data center, using 2400 MWh of electricity per day, can use up to 2,000,000 litres (530,000 US gal) of water per day.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] The electricity use is equivalent to that of 60,000–120,000 households in the U.S., while water use is equivalent about 6,500 households.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Water usage can be divided into three categories: on-site (direct usage from data centers), off-site (indirect usage from electricity), and supply-chain (water usage from manufacturing processes).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] On-site water use refers to the direct water consumed by the data center for the cooling of its equipment.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Water is used specifically for space humidification (adding moisture to the air), evaporative cooling systems (cooling air before entering server rooms), and cooling towers (removing heat from the facility).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Off-site water use is the indirect water usage from the electricity generated in data centers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] It is estimated that 56% of U.S. data centers' electricity comes from fossil fuels in thermal power stations, which use water to generate power via steam.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Lastly, data centers consume water through the process of AI chip and server manufacturing.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] These chips, specifically, consume a vast amount of ultrapure water for fabrication and cooling of semiconductor plants.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] While this scope of water usage is not as significant as on-site and off-site water usage, it is still a contributing factor.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Globally, since 2022, more than two-thirds of new data centers have been built in water-stressed areas, including Texas, Arizona, Saudi Arabia, and India, where freshwater scarcity is already a critical issue.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] The global water footprint of data centers is estimated at 560 billion litres (150×10^9 US gal) annually, a figure projected to double by 2030 due to increasing AI demand.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] In regions like Aragon, Spain, Amazon's planned data centers are licensed to withdraw 755,720 cubic metres (612.67 acre⋅ft) of water per year, sparking conflicts with farmers who rely on the same dwindling supplies.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Similar tensions have arisen in Chile, the Netherlands, and Uruguay, where communities protest the diversion of water for tech infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Tech companies, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon, have pledged to become "water positive" by 2030, aiming to replenish more water than they consume.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] However, critics argue that such commitments often rely on water offsetting, which does not address acute local shortages.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] At least 59 additional data centers are planned for water-stressed U.S. regions by 2028, and AI's global water demand is projected to reach 6.6 billion cubic metres (1,700×10^9 US gal) by 2027.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Data centers generate significant electronic waste (e-waste) due to the frequent replacement of hardware such as servers, GPUs, CPUs, memory, and storage devices, often every 2–5 years to meet demands for digital transformation and AI.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Globally, e-waste totaled 62 million metric tons in 2022, with generative AI projected to contribute 1.2 to 5 million metric tons annually by 2030, including valuable metals like copper and gold, and hazardous substances such as lead and mercury.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] In the U.S., data centers contribute to an annual loss of $10 billion in discarded e-waste value, including $4 billion in precious metals.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Only 22% of global e-waste is formally collected and recycled, exacerbating environmental pollution and health risks in informal processing sites, often in developing countries where exported waste is handled.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] From a political ecology perspective, data center e-waste highlights power imbalances in resource management and environmental justice, as tech corporations benefit from tax incentives while externalizing costs to marginalized communities through toxic exports and landfill burdens.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where shared resources like metals are depleted without equitable governance.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Mitigation strategies include modular hardware designs, secure data erasure for reuse, and extended producer responsibility policies to reduce waste by up to 86% in optimized scenarios.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] According to one 2025 energy model, the U.S. could see energy prices increase 8% nationally by 2030.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Higher electricity prices are already occurring in some regions, particularly those with lots of data centers like Santa Clara, California, and parts of upstate New York.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Data centers have also generated concerns in Northern Virginia about whether residents will have to foot the bill for future power lines.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] It has also made it harder to develop housing in London.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] A Bank of America Institute report in July 2024 found that increased demand for electricity due in part to AI has been pushing electricity prices higher and is a significant contributor to electricity inflation.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] A Harvard Law School report in March 2025 found that because utilities are increasingly in competition to attract data center contracts from big tech companies, they are likely hiding subsidies to those trillion-dollar companies in power prices by raising costs for American consumers.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Data centers have increasingly been analyzed through the lens of political ecology, which explores the intersections of power, politics, and environmental change in technological infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Scholars argue that these facilities reshape urban and rural landscapes by existing in marginalized or post-industrial areas, often repurposing abandoned sites while promising economic revitalization through job creation and tax revenues.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] For instance, hyperscale data centers in rural towns like Prineville, Oregon, or Luleå, Sweden, challenge traditional core-periphery dynamics but can exacerbate global inequalities in digital access and resource distribution.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] In the context of digital transformation, data centers enable the expansion of cloud computing, AI, and machine learning, but at significant ecological and social costs.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Critics from science and technology studies (STS) highlight how corporate sustainability pledges, such as carbon neutrality targets by companies like Microsoft and Google, often rely on offsets and renewable subsidies that privatize benefits while causing social and environmental harms.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where data centers' intensive use of public resources (like electricity grids and water supplies) represents an enclosure, with tech firms receiving tax breaks and priority access at the expense of local communities.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Jobs created by data centers tend to be temporary or few in number.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] A study found the productivity increases enabled by data centers are multiple times larger than gross external damages.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Social mobilizations against data centers help shape the discourse around growth of the industry, raise public awareness of issues data centers present, and may impact public policy.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Groups opposed to new data center projects have expressed concern that digital infrastructure exploits local resources 'to the benefit of actors and institutions residing elsewhere'.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] This may occur when data being processed in a facility belongs to actors in other countries, but local people bear the burdens of water and energy use.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] In the U.S., bipartisan community resistance to data center development has grown, with residents voicing concerns about water scarcity, rising utility bills, noise pollution, and urban sprawl.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Facilities in rural areas of the U.S. have been focal points for local resistance.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Data Center Watch reported that multiple projects collectively worth $64 billion had been stopped or delayed between May 2024 and March 2025.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] An additional $98 billion worth of projects were blocked or delayed between March and June 2025.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] A Gallup poll taken in March 2026 reported seven out of ten Americans oppose data center projects in their area.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Outside of the U.S., protests in the Netherlands led to a temporary national ban on new mega-centers in 2022.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] In Chile, protests by activists to protect water reserves led to Google withdrawing plans to build a data center.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] In the United Kingdom, "March Against the Machines" protests were held.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Residents have been concerned about air, water, and noise pollution, as well as property devaluation, traffic, and the risk of fires.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Other environmental concerns involving AI data centers include e-waste and the embodied energy of construction materials, such as concrete and cement.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] data center, they would orbit above the dawn / dusk transition of the planet.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Housing data centers in space has been proposed for low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] The theoretical advantages are that of space-based solar power, in addition to aiding in weather forecasting and weather prediction computation from weather satellites, and the ability to freely scale up.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] However, it is difficult to design cooling systems in space, as convection is not available and sunlight causes large temperature fluctuations.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] Other challenges include damage from cosmic rays and micrometeorites.
[src:azure-overview/data-center-p02] The design and shape of data centers could change rapidly in the not-too-distant future with the advent of new technologies, such as quantum computing, biocomputation, and synthetic DNA data storage, as examples.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure was first introduced at the Professional Developers Conference (PDC) in October 2008 under the code name "Project Red Dog".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] It was officially launched as Windows Azure in February 2010 and later renamed to Microsoft Azure on March 25, 2014.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure uses large-scale virtualization at Microsoft data centers worldwide and offers more than 600 services.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure offers a service level agreement (SLA) that guarantees 99.9% availability for applications and data hosted on its platform, subject to specific terms and conditions outlined in the SLA documentation.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The Microsoft Azure Service Bus allows applications running on Azure premises or off-premises devices to communicate with Azure.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] This helps to build scalable and reliable applications in a service-oriented architecture (SOA).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] A PaaS offering that can be used for encoding, content protection, streaming, or analytics.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure has a worldwide content delivery network (CDN) designed to efficiently deliver audio, video, applications, images, and other static files.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] It improves the performance of websites by caching static files closer to users, based on their geographic location.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Users can manage the network using a REST-based HTTP API.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure has 118 point-of-presence locations across 100 cities worldwide (also known as Edge locations) as of January 2023.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Through Azure Blockchain Workbench, Microsoft is providing the required infrastructure to set up a consortium network in multiple topologies using a variety of consensus mechanisms.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft provides integration from these blockchain platforms to other Microsoft services to streamline the development of distributed applications.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft supports many general-purpose blockchains, including Ethereum and Hyperledger Fabric and purpose-built blockchains like Corda.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure functions are used in serverless computing architectures, where subscribers can execute code as an event-driven Function-as-a-Service (FaaS) without managing the underlying server resources.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Customers using Azure functions are billed based on per-second resource consumption and executions.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure Local (previously Azure Stack HCI) is a hyper-converged infrastructure (HCI) product that uses validated hardware to run virtualized workloads on-premises to consolidate aging infrastructure and connect to Azure for cloud services.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Launched in September 2020, Azure Orbital lets private industries and government agencies process satellite data quickly by connecting directly to cloud computing networks.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Mobile cloud computing ground stations are also available to provide connectivity to remote locations without ground infrastructure.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Third-party satellite systems, like SpaceX's Starlink and SES' O3b constellation, can be employed.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] SES plans to use Microsoft's data centers to provide cloud connectivity to remote areas through its next generation O3b mPOWER MEO satellites alongside Microsoft's data centers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The company will deploy satellite control and uplink ground stations to achieve this.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] SES launched the first two O3b mPOWER satellites in December 2022; nine more are scheduled between 2023 and 2024.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] According to Microsoft, satellite cloud connectivity can provide lower latency than terrestrial fiber routes in specific regions.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The company stated that during network testing for Xbox Cloud, satellite connections out-performed terrestrial networks in certain rural or geographically remote areas of the United States due to fewer network routing hops.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure Orbital was retired in December 2024, with existing assets being sold off to Space Leasing International.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In August 2024, Azure launched Azure Container Storage, a platform-managed container-native storage service for the public cloud.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The service supports Ephemeral Disks (Local NVMe/Temp SSD) and Azure Disks for containerized applications.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure Quantum provides access to quantum hardware and software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The platform provides access to third-party quantum systems utilizing varied hardware architectures, including trapped ion, neutral atom, and superconducting systems.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In 2021, Microsoft developed the quantum programming language Q# (pronounced Q Sharp) and an open-source quantum development kit for algorithm development and simulation.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In 2023, Microsoft developed Quantum Intermediate Representation (QIR) from LLVM as a common interface between programming languages and target quantum processors.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The Azure Quantum Resource Estimator estimates the resources required to execute a given quantum algorithm on a fault-tolerant quantum computer.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] It can also show how future quantum computers will impact today's encryption algorithms.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] As of 2018, Azure was available in 54 regions, and Microsoft was the first primary cloud provider to establish facilities in Africa, with two regions in South Africa.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure geographies consist of multiple Azure Regions, like "North Europe" (located in Dublin, Ireland) and "West Europe" (located in Amsterdam, Netherlands).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] On June 19, 2019, Microsoft announced the launch of two new cloud regions in the United Arab Emirates – Microsoft's first in the Middle East.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] On March 6, 2025, the company announced a strategic partnership with the Government of Kuwait, represented by the Central Agency for Information Technology (CAIT) and the Communication and Information Technology Regulatory Authority (CITRA).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] This collaboration aims to accelerate digital transformation efforts aligned with Kuwait's Vision 2035.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The partnership will focus on creating an AI-powered Azure Region to enhance local AI capabilities, stimulate economic growth, and drive innovation across various industries.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho collaborated with Microsoft to deploy an aquaculture water management system using Azure IoT and machine learning applications.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Developed alongside researchers from Kindai University, the system uses computer vision on water pump conveyor belts to log fish counts, monitor stock quantities, and track automated water flow metrics via the Azure Machine Learning and Azure IoT Hub services.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure utilizes a specialized operating system with the same name to power its "fabric layer".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] This cluster is hosted at Microsoft's data centers and is responsible for managing computing and storage resources and allocating them to applications running on the Microsoft Azure platform.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] It is a "cloud layer" built upon various Windows Server systems, including the customized Microsoft Azure Hypervisor, which is based on Windows Server 2008 and enables the virtualization of services.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The Microsoft Azure Fabric Controller maintains the scalability and dependability of services and environments in the data center.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] It prevents failure in server malfunction and manages users' web applications, including memory allocation and load balancing.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Azure provides an API built on REST, HTTP, and XML that allows a developer to interact with the services offered by Microsoft Azure.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft also provides a client-side managed class library that encapsulates the functions of interacting with the services.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] It also integrates with Microsoft Visual Studio, Git, and Eclipse.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Users can manage Azure services in multiple ways, one of which is through the Web-based Azure Portal, which became generally available in December 2015.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Apart from accessing services via API, users can browse active resources, adjust settings, launch new resources, and view primary monitoring data of functional virtual machines and services using the portal.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Regarding cloud resources, Microsoft Azure offers two deployment models: the "classic" model and the Azure Resource Manager.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In the classic model, each resource, like a virtual machine or SQL database, had to be managed separately, but in 2014, Azure introduced the Azure Resource Manager, which allows users to group related services.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] This update makes it easier and more efficient to deploy, manage, and monitor resources that work closely together.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The classic model will eventually be phased out.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In January 2025, Microsoft announced plans to invest $80 billion in AI and data centers as part of its fiscal year 2025 budget.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] This investment would enhance the scalability and performance of Azure's cloud infrastructure, which supports AI-driven applications, including services developed through Microsoft's partnership with OpenAI.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In 2005, Microsoft took over Groove Networks, and Bill Gates made Groove's founder Ray Ozzie one of his 5 direct reports as one of 3 chief technology officers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Ozzie met with Amitabh Srivastava, which let Srivastava change course.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] They convinced Dave Cutler to postpone his retirement, and their teams developed a cloud operating system.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] At fiscal year-end 2025, Microsoft reported that Azure surpassed US$75 billion in annual revenue and operated over 400 datacenters across 70 regions.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] According to the Patriot Act, Microsoft has acknowledged that the U.S. government can access data even if the hosting company is not American and the data is outside the U.S.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] To address concerns related to privacy and security, Microsoft has established the Microsoft Azure Trust Center.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure offers services that comply with multiple compliance programs, including ISO 27001:2005 and HIPAA.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] A comprehensive and up-to-date list of these services is available on the Microsoft Azure Trust Center Compliance page.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure received JAB Provisional Authority to Operate (P-ATO) from the U.S. government under the Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) guidelines.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] This program provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud services used by the federal government.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In 2025, an activist campaign named "No Azure for Apartheid" accused Microsoft of providing cloud and AI services to entities involved in Israeli policies within the Palestinian territories.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Campaign organizers argue that Azure's technology could enable surveillance and displacement, drawing parallels to historical corporate involvement in apartheid regimes.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Similar activism has targeted other technology companies, such as the No Tech for Apartheid movement directed at Google and Amazon, though critics state that Microsoft's specific government contracts and military partnerships draw heightened scrutiny.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Protesters have demanded transparency, ethical oversight, and the termination of contracts that they state facilitate human rights violations.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft has stated that its operations comply with international laws and regulations.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The following is a list of Microsoft Azure outages and service disruptions.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] A large variety of Azure certifications can be attained, each requiring one or multiple successfully completed examinations.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Certification levels range from beginner, intermediate to expert.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure's services can have varied and complex pricing models.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In August 2021, researchers from Wiz Research claimed to have discovered a vulnerability in the Azure Cosmos DB database, referred to as "ChaosDB." They claimed that they had gained complete unrestricted access to the accounts and databases of several thousand Microsoft Azure customers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In August 2021, Microsoft claimed they mitigated the vulnerability and no customer data was accessed.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, researchers from Palo Alto Networks claimed to discover a significant cross-account takeover vulnerability in Azure Container Instances, named "Azurescape".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] According to Palo Alto Networks' researchers, this vulnerability is the first known instance that allows one user of a public cloud service to escape their environment and execute code on other users' environments within the same service.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] Although Microsoft quickly patched the issue, Palo Alto Networks advised Azure customers to revoke any privileged credentials deployed before August 31, 2021, as a precaution.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, Microsoft claimed they fixed the vulnerability.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, researchers from Wiz Research claimed they found four critical vulnerabilities in the Open Management Infrastructure (OMI), which is Azure's software agent deployed on a large portion of Linux VMs in Azure.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] The researchers named it "OMIGOD" and claimed that these vulnerabilities allowed for remote code execution within the Azure network and could escalate privileges to root.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] They claimed that the vulnerabilities affected various Azure services, including Azure Log Analytics, Azure Diagnostics, and Azure Security Center.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-azure] In response, Microsoft announced that it had released fixes for the aforementioned vulnerabilities in September 2021.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Founded in 1975 by Bill Gates and Paul Allen to market BASIC interpreters for the Altair 8800, Microsoft rose to dominate the PC operating system market with MS-DOS in the mid-1980s, followed by Windows.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The company's 1986 initial public offering (IPO) and subsequent rise in its share price created three billionaires and an estimated 12,000 millionaires among Microsoft employees.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Since the 1990s, it has increasingly diversified its business.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Steve Ballmer replaced Gates as CEO in 2000.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] He oversaw the then-largest of Microsoft's corporate acquisitions in Skype Technologies in 2011, an increased focus on hardware that led to its first in-house PC line—the Surface—in 2012, and the formation of Microsoft Mobile through Nokia.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Since Satya Nadella became CEO in 2014, the company has changed focus towards cloud computing and acquired LinkedIn in 2016.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Under his direction, the company has expanded its video gaming business to support the Xbox brand, establishing the Microsoft Gaming division in 2022 and acquiring Activision Blizzard in 2023.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft has been dominant in the IBM PC–compatible operating system and office software suite markets since the 1990s.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Its best-known software products are the Windows line of operating systems and the Microsoft Office and Microsoft 365 suite of productivity applications, which most notably include the Word word processor, Excel spreadsheet editor, and PowerPoint presentation program.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Its flagship hardware products are the Surface lineup of PCs and the Xbox brand of video game consoles, the latter including the Xbox network.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The company also provides a range of consumer Internet services such as Bing web search, the MSN web portal, the Outlook.com (Hotmail) email service, and the Microsoft Store.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In the enterprise and development fields, Microsoft most notably provides the Azure cloud computing platform, Microsoft SQL Server database software, and Visual Studio.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft became the third publicly traded U.S. company to be valued at over $1 trillion in April 2019.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] It has been criticized for monopolistic practices, and the company's software received criticism for problems with ease of use, robustness, and security.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft has also been criticized for its role in providing services to Israel during the Gaza war.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Childhood friends Bill Gates and Paul Allen sought to make a business using their skills in computer programming.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In 1972, they founded Traf-O-Data, which sold a rudimentary computer to track and analyze automobile traffic data.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The January 1975 issue of *Popular Electronics* featured Micro Instrumentation and Telemetry Systems's (MITS) Altair 8800 microcomputer, which inspired Allen to suggest that they could program a BASIC interpreter for the device.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Gates called MITS and claimed that he had a working interpreter, and MITS requested a demonstration.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Allen worked on a simulator for the Altair while Gates developed the interpreter, and it worked flawlessly when they demonstrated it to MITS in March 1975 in Albuquerque, New Mexico.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] MITS agreed to distribute it, marketing it as Altair BASIC.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Gates and Allen established Microsoft on April 4, 1975, with Gates as CEO, and Allen suggested the name "Micro-Soft", short for micro-computer software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In August 1977, the company formed an agreement with ASCII Magazine in Japan, resulting in its first international office of ASCII Microsoft.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft moved its headquarters to Bellevue, Washington, in January 1979.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft entered the operating system (OS) business in 1980 with its own version of Unix, licensed from AT&T Corporation a year before, called Xenix, but it was MS-DOS that solidified the company's dominance.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] IBM awarded a contract to Microsoft in November 1980 to provide a version of the CP/M OS to be used in the IBM Personal Computer (IBM PC).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] For this deal, Microsoft purchased a CP/M clone called 86-DOS from Seattle Computer Products which it branded as MS-DOS, although IBM rebranded it to IBM PC DOS.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft retained ownership of MS-DOS following the release of the IBM PC in August 1981.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] IBM had copyrighted the IBM PC BIOS, so other companies had to reverse engineer it for non-IBM hardware to run as IBM PC compatibles, but no such restriction applied to the operating systems.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The company expanded into new markets with the release of the Microsoft Mouse in 1983, as well as with a publishing division named Microsoft Press.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Paul Allen resigned from Microsoft in 1983 after developing Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft released Windows 1.0 on November 20, 1985, as a graphical extension for MS-DOS, despite having begun jointly developing OS/2 with IBM that August.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft released its version of OS/2 to original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) on April 2, 1987.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In 1990, the Federal Trade Commission examined Microsoft for possible collusion due to the partnership with IBM, marking the beginning of more than a decade of legal clashes with the government.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Meanwhile, the company was at work on Microsoft Windows NT, which was heavily based on its copy of the OS/2 code.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] It shipped on July 21, 1993, with a new modular kernel and the 32-bit Win32 application programming interface (API), making it easier to port from 16-bit (MS-DOS-based) Windows.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft informed IBM of Windows NT, and the OS/2 partnership deteriorated.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In 1990, Microsoft introduced the Microsoft Office suite which bundled separate applications such as Microsoft Word and Microsoft Excel.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On May 22, Microsoft launched Windows 3.0, featuring streamlined user interface graphics and improved protected mode capability for the Intel 386 processor, and both Office and Windows became dominant in their respective areas.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Following Bill Gates's internal "Internet Tidal Wave memo" on May 26, 1995, Microsoft began to redefine its offerings and expand its product line into computer networking and the World Wide Web.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] With a few exceptions of new companies, like Netscape, Microsoft was the only major and established company that acted fast enough to be a part of the World Wide Web practically from the start.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Other companies like Borland, WordPerfect, Novell, IBM and Lotus, being much slower to adapt to the new situation, would give Microsoft market dominance.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The company released Windows 95 on August 24, 1995, featuring pre-emptive multitasking, a completely new user interface with a novel start button, and 32-bit compatibility; similar to NT, it provided the Win32 API.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Windows 95 came bundled with the online service MSN, which was intended to be a competitor to services such as CompuServe and AOL.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The web browser Internet Explorer was not bundled with the retail release of Windows 95, and was instead included in the later Microsoft Plus! pack, as well as with OEM releases of Windows 95.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Backed by a high-profile marketing campaign and what *The New York Times* called "the splashiest, most frenzied, most expensive introduction of a computer product in the industry's history," Windows 95 quickly became a success.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Branching out into new markets in 1996, Microsoft and General Electric's NBC unit created a new 24/7 cable news channel, MSNBC.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft created Windows CE 1.0, a new OS designed for devices with low memory and other constraints, such as personal digital assistants.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In October 1997, the Justice Department filed a motion in the Federal District Court, stating that Microsoft violated an agreement signed in 1994 and asked the court to stop the bundling of Internet Explorer with Windows.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On January 13, 2000, Bill Gates handed over the CEO position to Steve Ballmer, an old college friend of Gates and employee of the company since 1980, while creating a new position for himself as Chief Software Architect.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Under Ballmer's leadership, the company saw an increased focus on hardware products.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On October 25, 2001, Microsoft released Windows XP, unifying the mainstream and NT lines of OS under the NT codebase.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The company released the Xbox later that year, entering the video game console market dominated by Sony and Nintendo.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In November 2005, the company's second and most successful video game console, the Xbox 360, was released.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Increasingly present in the hardware business following Xbox, Microsoft 2006 released the Zune series of digital media players, a successor of its previous software platform Portable Media Center.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Released in January 2007, the next version of Windows, Vista, focused on features, security and a redesigned user interface dubbed Aero.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft Office 2007, released at the same time, featured a "Ribbon" user interface which was a significant departure from its predecessors.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Relatively strong sales of both products helped to produce a record profit in 2007.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The European Union imposed another fine of €899 million ($1.4 billion) for Microsoft's lack of compliance with the March 2004 judgment on February 27, 2008, saying that the company charged rivals unreasonable prices for key information about its workgroup and backoffice servers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft stated that it was in compliance and that "these fines are about the past issues that have been resolved".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Gates retired from his role as Chief Software Architect on June 27, 2008, a decision announced in June 2006, while retaining other positions related to the company in addition to being an advisor for the company on key projects.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Azure Services Platform, the company's entry into the cloud computing market for Windows, launched on October 27, 2008.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On February 12, 2009, Microsoft announced its intent to open a chain of Microsoft-branded retail stores, and on October 22, 2009, the first retail Microsoft Store opened in Scottsdale, Arizona; the same day Windows 7 was officially released to the public.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] As the smartphone industry boomed in the late 2000s, Microsoft had struggled to keep up with its rivals in providing a modern smartphone operating system, falling behind Apple and Google-sponsored Android in the United States.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] As a result, in 2010 Microsoft revamped its aging flagship mobile operating system, Windows Mobile, replacing it with the new Windows Phone OS that was released in October that year.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] It used a new user interface design language, codenamed "Metro", which prominently used simple shapes, typography, and iconography, utilizing the concept of minimalism.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft implemented a new strategy for the software industry, providing a consistent user experience across all smartphones using the Windows Phone OS.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] It launched an alliance with Nokia in 2011 and Microsoft worked closely with the company to co-develop Windows Phone, but remained partners with long-time Windows Mobile OEM HTC.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft is a founding member of the Open Networking Foundation started on March 23, 2011.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] This nonprofit organization is focused on providing support for a cloud computing initiative called Software-Defined Networking.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The initiative is meant to speed innovation through simple software changes in telecommunications networks, wireless networks, data centers, and other networking areas.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Following the release of Windows Phone, Microsoft undertook a gradual rebranding of its product range throughout 2011 and 2012, with the corporation's logos, products, services, and websites adopting the principles and concepts of the Metro design language.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft unveiled Windows 8, an operating system designed to power both personal computers and tablet computers, in Taipei in June 2011.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Also in 2011, Microsoft saw its largest acquisition by taking over Skype.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The Surface was unveiled in June 2012, becoming the first computer in the company's history to have its hardware made by Microsoft.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On June 25, Microsoft paid US$1.2 billion to buy the social network Yammer.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On July 31, it launched the Outlook.com webmail service to compete with Gmail.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On September 4, 2012, Microsoft released Windows Server 2012.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In July 2012, Microsoft sold its 50% stake in MSNBC, which it had run as a joint venture with NBC since 1996.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In October 2012, Microsoft launched Windows 8, Microsoft Surface, and Windows Phone 8.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] To cope with the potential for an increase in demand for products and services, Microsoft opened a number of "holiday stores" across the U.S. to complement the increasing number of "bricks-and-mortar" Microsoft Stores that opened in 2012.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On March 29, 2013, Microsoft launched a Patent Tracker.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In August 2012, the New York City Police Department announced a partnership with Microsoft for the development of the Domain Awareness System which is used for police surveillance in New York City.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The Kinect, a motion-sensing input device made by Microsoft and designed as a video game controller, first introduced in November 2010, was upgraded for the 2013 release of the Xbox One video game console.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On July 19, 2013, Microsoft stocks suffered its biggest one-day percentage sell-off since the year 2000, after its fourth-quarter report raised concerns among investors on the poor showings of both Windows 8 and the Surface tablet.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft suffered a loss of more than US$32 billion.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In line with the maturing PC business, in July 2013, Microsoft announced that it would reorganize into four new business divisions: Operating Systems, Apps, Cloud, and Devices.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] All previous divisions were dissolved into new divisions without any workforce cuts.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On September 3, 2013, Microsoft agreed to buy Nokia's mobile unit for $7 billion, following Amy Hood taking the role of CFO.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On February 4, 2014, Steve Ballmer stepped down as CEO of Microsoft and was succeeded by Satya Nadella, who previously led Microsoft's Cloud and Enterprise division.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Thompson took on the role of chairman, in place of Bill Gates, who continued to participate as a technology advisor.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Thompson became the second chairman in Microsoft's history.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On April 25, 2014, Microsoft acquired Nokia Devices and Services for $7.2 billion.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] This new subsidiary was renamed Microsoft Mobile Oy.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On September 15, 2014, Microsoft acquired the video game development company Mojang, best known for *Minecraft*, for $2.5 billion.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Since Nadella became CEO, the company has changed focus towards cloud computing.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On January 21, 2015, Microsoft announced the release of its first interactive whiteboard, named Surface Hub.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On July 29, 2015, Windows 10 was released, with its server sibling, Windows Server 2016, released in September 2016.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft's share of the U.S. smartphone market in January 2016 was 2.7%.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] During the summer of 2015 the company lost $7.6 billion related to its mobile-phone business, firing 7,800 employees.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In 2015, the construction of a data center in Mecklenburg County, Virginia, led to the destruction of a historic African American cemetery despite archeological recommendations for preservation.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On March 1, 2016, Microsoft announced the merger of its PC and Xbox divisions, with Phil Spencer announcing that Universal Windows Platform (UWP) apps would be the focus for Microsoft's gaming in the future.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft also aqcuired LinkedIn in 2016.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On January 24, 2017, Microsoft showcased Intune for Education at the BETT 2017 education technology conference in London.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Intune for Education is a new cloud-based application and device management service for the education sector.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In May 2016, the company announced it was laying off 1,850 workers, and taking an impairment and restructuring charge of $950 million.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In June 2016, Microsoft announced a project named Microsoft Azure Information Protection.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] It aims to help enterprises protect their data as it moves between servers and devices.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In November 2016, Microsoft joined the Linux Foundation as a Platinum member during Microsoft's Connect(); developer event in New York.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The cost of each Platinum membership is US$500,000 per year.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Some analysts had deemed this unthinkable ten years prior, however, as in 2001 then-CEO Steve Ballmer called Linux "cancer".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In January 2018, Microsoft patched Windows 10 to account for CPU problems related to Intel's Meltdown security breach.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The patch led to issues with the Microsoft Azure virtual machines reliant on Intel's CPU architecture.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On January 12, Microsoft released PowerShell Core 6.0 for the macOS and Linux operating systems.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In February 2018, Microsoft ceased notification support for its Windows Phone devices which effectively ended firmware updates for the discontinued devices.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In March 2018, Microsoft recalled Windows 10 S to change it to a mode for the Windows operating system rather than a separate and unique operating system.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In March the company also established guidelines that censor users of Office 365 from using profanity in private documents.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In April 2018, Microsoft released the source code for Windows File Manager under the MIT License to celebrate the program's 20th anniversary.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In April the company further expressed willingness to embrace open source initiatives by announcing Azure Sphere as its own derivative of the Linux operating system.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In May 2018, Microsoft partnered with 17 American intelligence agencies to develop cloud computing products.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The project is dubbed "Azure Government" and has ties to the Joint Enterprise Defense Infrastructure (JEDI) surveillance program.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On June 4, 2018, Microsoft officially announced the acquisition of GitHub for $7.5 billion, a deal that closed on October 26, 2018.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On July 10, 2018, Microsoft revealed the Surface Go platform to the public.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] A free version of Teams was released on July 12, 2018.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In August 2018, Microsoft released two projects called Microsoft AccountGuard and Defending Democracy.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] It also unveiled Snapdragon 850 compatibility for Windows 10 on the ARM architecture.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for Internet of things (IoT) technologies related to water management.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In September 2018, Microsoft discontinued Skype Classic.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On October 10, 2018, Microsoft joined the Open Invention Network community despite holding more than 60,000 patents.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In December 2018, Microsoft announced Project Mu, an open source release of the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) core used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The project promotes the idea of Firmware as a Service.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In the same month, Microsoft announced the open source implementation of Windows Forms and the Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) which will allow for further movement of the company toward the transparent release of key frameworks used in developing Windows desktop applications and software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] December also saw the company discontinue the Microsoft Edge [Legacy] browser project in favor of the "New Edge" browser project, featuring a Chromium based backend.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In February 2019, hundreds of Microsoft employees protested the company's war profiteering from a $480 million contract to develop virtual reality headsets for the United States Army.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On August 5, 2020, Microsoft stopped its xCloud game streaming test for iOS devices.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Apple imposed a strict limit on "remote desktop clients" which means applications are only allowed to connect to a user-owned host device or gaming console owned by the user.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On September 21, 2020, Microsoft announced its intent to acquire video game company ZeniMax Media, the parent company of Bethesda Softworks.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On March 9, 2021, the acquisition was finalized at $8.1 billion and ZeniMax Media became part of Microsoft's Xbox Game Studios division.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On November 10, 2020, Microsoft released the Xbox Series X and Xbox Series S video game consoles.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In February 2021, Microsoft released Azure Quantum for public preview.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The public cloud computing platform provides access to quantum software and quantum hardware including trapped ion, neutral atom, and superconducting systems.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In April 2021, Microsoft announced it would buy Nuance Communications for approximately $16 billion, completing the acquisition in March 2022.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In 2021, in part due to the strong quarterly earnings spurred by the COVID-19 pandemic, Microsoft's valuation came to nearly $2 trillion.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The increased necessity for remote work and distance education drove demand for cloud computing and grew the company's gaming sales.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On June 24, 2021, Microsoft announced Windows 11 during a livestreamed event.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The announcement came with confusion after Microsoft announced Windows 10 would be the last version of the operating system.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] It was released to the general public on October 5, 2021.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In September 2021, it was announced that the company had acquired TakeLessons, an online platform that connects students and tutors in numerous subjects.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The acquisition positioned Microsoft to grow its presence in the market of providing online education to large numbers of people.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In the same month, Microsoft acquired Australia-based video editing software company Clipchamp.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In October 2021, Microsoft announced that it began rolling out end-to-end encryption (E2EE) support for Microsoft Teams calls in order to secure business communication while using video conferencing software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On October 7, Microsoft acquired Ally.io, a software service that measures companies' progress against OKRs, planning to incorporate it into its Viva family of employee experience products.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On January 18, 2022, Microsoft announced the acquisition of American video game developer and holding company Activision Blizzard in an all-cash deal worth $68.7 billion, which was completed in 2023.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft also named Phil Spencer, head of the Xbox brand since 2014, the inaugural CEO of the newly established Microsoft Gaming division, which now houses the Xbox operations team and the three publishers in the company's portfolio (Xbox Game Studios, ZeniMax Media, Activision Blizzard).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft had not released statements regarding Activision's recent legal controversies regarding employee abuse, but reports have alleged that Activision CEO Bobby Kotick, a major target of the controversy, would leave the company after the acquisition is finalized.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The deal was closed on October 13, 2023.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In January 2023, CEO Satya Nadella announced Microsoft would lay off 10,000 employees.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The announcement came a day after hosting a Sting concert for 50 people, including Microsoft executives, in Davos, Switzerland.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On January 23, 2023, Microsoft announced a new multi-year, multi-billion dollar investment deal with ChatGPT developer OpenAI.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In June 2023, Microsoft released Azure Quantum Elements to run molecular simulations and calculations in computational chemistry and materials science using a combination of AI, high-performance computing and quantum computing.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The service includes Copilot, a GPT-4 based large language model tool to query and visualize data, write code, initiate simulations, and educate researchers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] At a November 2023 developer conference, Microsoft announced two new custom-designed computing chips: The Maia chip, designed to run large language models, and Cobalt CPU, designed to power general cloud services on Azure.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On November 20, 2023, Satya Nadella announced that Sam Altman, who had been ousted as CEO of OpenAI just days earlier, and Greg Brockman, who had resigned as president, would join Microsoft to lead a new advanced AI research team.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] However, the plan was short-lived, as Altman was subsequently reinstated as OpenAI's CEO and Brockman rejoined the company amid pressure from OpenAI's employees and investors on its board.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In March 2024, Inflection AI's cofounders Mustafa Suleyman and Karen Simonyan announced their departure from the company in order to start Microsoft AI, with Microsoft acqui-hiring nearly the entirety of its 70-person workforce.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] As part of the deal, Microsoft paid Inflection $650 million to license its technology.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In January 2024, Microsoft became the most valued publicly traded company.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Meanwhile, that month, the company announced a subscription offering of artificial intelligence for small businesses via Copilot Pro.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In June 2024, Microsoft announced it would be laying off 1,000 employees from the company's mixed reality and Azure cloud computing divisions.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The same month, Microsoft announced that it was building a "hyperscale data centre" in South East Leeds.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In July 2024, it was reported that the company was laying off its diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) team.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On July 19, a global IT outage impacted Microsoft services, affecting businesses, airlines, and financial institutions worldwide.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The outage was traced back to a flawed update of CrowdStrike's cybersecurity software, which resulted in Microsoft systems crashing and causing disruptions across various sectors.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Despite CrowdStrike's CEO George Kurtz clarifying that the issue was not a cyberattack, the incident had widespread consequences, leading to delays in air travel, financial transactions, and medical services globally.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft stated that the underlying cause had been fixed but acknowledged ongoing residual impacts on some Microsoft 365 apps and services.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In September 2024, BlackRock and Microsoft announced a $30 billion fund, the Global AI Infrastructure Investment Partnership, to invest in AI infrastructure such as data centers and energy projects.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Partners include Abu Dhabi-backed MGX and Nvidia, which will provide AI expertise.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Investments will primarily focus on the U.S., with some in partner countries.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft also announced relaunch of its controversial tool, Recall, in November 2024 after addressing privacy concerns.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Initially criticized for taking regular screenshots without user consent, Recall was changed to an opt-in feature instead of being default on.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The UK's Information Commissioner's Office monitored the situation and noted the adjustments, which included enhanced security measures like encryption and biometric access.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] While experts regarded these changes as improvements, they advised caution, with some recommending further testing before users opted in.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On February 28, 2025, Microsoft announced that Skype would be shutting down on May 5, 2025, to streamline its focus on Microsoft Teams.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The company stated there would be no job cuts due to the shutdown.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In mid-2025, Microsoft's Russian division, Microsoft Rus LLC, filed for bankruptcy after President Vladimir Putin stated that foreign services providers should be throttled in Russia to make way for domestic software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The company had restructured operations in Russia after the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, but those restructuring efforts had failed.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On May 23, 2025, it was reported that Europol's European Cybercrime Centre worked with Microsoft to disrupt Lumma Stealer, a significant infostealer threat.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The joint operation targeted a sophisticated ecosystem that allowed criminals to exploit stolen information on a massive scale.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On July 2, 2025, Microsoft announced it would cut nearly 4% of its workforce, around 9,000 jobs, to control costs amid heavy AI infrastructure spending, while also restructuring management and streamlining operations.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] According to an analysis by Bridgewater Associates, Microsoft—along with Amazon, Alphabet and Meta—is expected to collectively invest about $650 billion to scale up AI-related infrastructure in 2026.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In March 2026, Microsoft-controlled discussion forums banned the nickname *Microslop*, used to express pushback against Microsoft's Copilot-based and GenAI efforts.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In March 2026, Microsoft signed an energy pledge at the White House which required it to bear the cost of new electricity generation to power its data centers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On 9 March 2026, Microsoft unveiled the Copilot Cowork tool, which is based on Claude Cowork, tapping into the growing demand for autonomous agents.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] 14 in the 2022 *Fortune* 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue; and it was the world's largest software maker by revenue in 2022 according to *Forbes* Global 2000.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In 2018, Microsoft became the most valuable publicly traded company in the world, a position it has repeatedly traded with Apple in the years since.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In April 2019, Microsoft became the third U.S. public company to be valued at over $1 trillion.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] As of 2024, Microsoft has the third-highest global brand valuation.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft is one of only two U.S.-based companies that have a prime credit rating of AAA.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The company is run by a board of directors made up of mostly company outsiders, as is customary for publicly traded companies.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Members of the board of directors as of December 2023 are Satya Nadella, Reid Hoffman, Hugh Johnston, Teri List, Sandi Peterson, Penny Pritzker, Carlos Rodriguez, Charles Scharf, John W.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Thompson, Emma Walmsley and Padmasree Warrior.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Board members are elected every year at the annual shareholders' meeting using a majority vote system.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] There are four committees within the board that oversee more specific matters.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On March 13, 2020, Gates announced that he is leaving the board of directors of Microsoft and Berkshire Hathaway to focus more on his philanthropic efforts.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] When Microsoft went public and launched its initial public offering (IPO) in 1986, the opening stock price was $21; after the trading day, the price closed at $27.75.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] As of July 2010, with the company's nine stock splits, any IPO shares would be multiplied by 288; if one were to buy the IPO today, given the splits and other factors, it would cost about 9 cents.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The stock price peaked in 1999 at around $119 ($60.928, adjusting for splits).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Though the company had subsequent increases in dividend payouts, the price of Microsoft's stock remained steady for years.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Standard & Poor's and Moody's Investors Service have both given a AAA rating to Microsoft, whose assets were valued at $41 billion as compared to only $8.5 billion in unsecured debt.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Consequently, in February 2011 Microsoft released a corporate bond amounting to $2.25 billion with relatively low borrowing rates compared to government bonds.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] For the first time in 20 years Apple Inc. surpassed Microsoft in Q1 2011 quarterly profits and revenues due to a slowdown in PC sales and continuing huge losses in Microsoft's Online Services Division (which contains its search engine Bing).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft profits were $5.2 billion, while Apple Inc. profits were $6 billion, on revenues of $14.5 billion and $24.7 billion respectively.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft's Online Services Division has been continuously loss-making since 2006 and in Q1 2011 it lost $726 million.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] This follows a loss of $2.5 billion for the year 2010.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On July 20, 2012, Microsoft posted its first quarterly loss ever, despite earning record revenues for the quarter and fiscal year, with a net loss of $492 million due to a writedown related to the advertising company aQuantive, which had been acquired for $6.2 billion back in 2007.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] As of January 2014, Microsoft's market capitalization stood at $314B, making it the 8th-largest company in the world by market capitalization.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In November 2014, Microsoft overtook ExxonMobil to become the second most-valuable company by market capitalization, behind only Apple Inc.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Its total market value was over $410B—with the stock price hitting $50.04 a share, the highest since early 2000.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In 2015, Reuters reported that Microsoft had earnings abroad of $76.4 billion which were untaxed by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Under U.S. law, corporations do not pay income tax on overseas profits until the profits are brought into the United States.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In November 2018, the company won a $480 million military contract with the U.S. government to bring augmented reality (AR) headset technology into the weapon repertoires of American soldiers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The two-year contract may result in follow-on orders of more than 100,000 headsets, according to documentation describing the bidding process.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] One of the contract's tag lines for the augmented reality technology seems to be its ability to enable "25 bloodless battles before the 1st battle", suggesting that actual combat training is going to be an essential aspect of the augmented reality headset capabilities.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] As such, it needs subsidiaries present in whatever national markets it chooses to harvest.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] An example is Microsoft Canada, which it established in 1985.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Other countries have similar installations, to funnel profits back up to Redmond and to distribute the dividends to the holders of MSFT stock.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In FY 2025, Microsoft spent over 25 billion dollars on marketing, or over 15 % of its expenses, compared to over 30 billion dollars spent on research and development.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft employed over 40 thousand people in marketing and sales.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Another study, released by the Open Source Development Labs, claimed that the Microsoft studies were "simply outdated and one-sided" and its survey concluded that the TCO of Linux was lower due to Linux administrators managing more servers on average and other reasons.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In July 2014, Microsoft announced plans to lay off 18,000 employees.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft employed 127,104 people as of June 5, 2014, making this about a 14 percent reduction of its workforce as the biggest Microsoft layoff ever.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] This included 12,500 professional and factory personnel.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Previously, Microsoft had eliminated 5,800 jobs in 2009 in line with the Great Recession of 2008–2017.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In September 2014, Microsoft laid off 2,100 people, including 747 people in the Seattle–Redmond area, where the company is headquartered.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The firings came as a second wave of the layoffs that were previously announced.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] This brought the total number to over 15,000 out of the 18,000 expected cuts.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In October 2014, Microsoft revealed that it was almost done with eliminating 18,000 employees, which was its largest-ever layoff sweep.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In July 2015, Microsoft announced another 7,800 job cuts in the next several months.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In May 2016, Microsoft announced another 1,850 job cuts mostly in its Nokia mobile phone division.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] As a result, the company will record an impairment and restructuring charge of approximately $950 million, of which approximately $200 million will relate to severance payments.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft laid off 1,900 employees in its gaming division in January 2024.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The layoffs primarily affected Activision Blizzard employees, but some Xbox and ZeniMax employees were also affected.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Blizzard president Mike Ybarra and chief design officer Allen Adham also resigned.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In May 2025, Microsoft announced that it is laying off more than 6,000 employees, around three percent of the company's entire workforce.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In July 2025, Microsoft announced another round of layoffs, cutting approximately 9,000 employees in its largest workforce reduction in over two years.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The cuts affected multiple divisions, including Xbox, with 830 positions eliminated at its Redmond, Washington headquarters.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Amid the layoffs, Microsoft also closed its office in Pakistan and laid off its employees there as part of its move toward a software-as-a-service and AI operating model.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft recognizes seven trade unions representing 1,750 workers in the United States at its video game subsidiaries Activision Blizzard and ZeniMax Media.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] U.S. workers have been vocal in opposing military and law-enforcement contracts with Microsoft.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Bethesda Game Studios is unionized in Canada.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft South Korea has recognized its union since 2017.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] German employees have elected works councils since 1998.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft provides information about reported bugs in its software to intelligence agencies of the United States government, prior to the public release of the fix.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] A Microsoft spokesperson stated that the corporation runs several programs that facilitate the sharing of such information with the U.S. government.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Following media reports about PRISM, NSA's massive electronic surveillance program, in May 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including Microsoft.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] According to leaks of said program, Microsoft joined the PRISM program in 2007.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] During the first six months of 2013, Microsoft received requests that affected between 15,000 and 15,999 accounts.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In December 2013, the company made a statement to further emphasize that it takes its customers' privacy and data protection very seriously, saying that "government snooping potentially now constitutes an 'advanced persistent threat,' alongside sophisticated malware and cyber attacks".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The statement also marked the beginning of three-part program to enhance Microsoft's encryption and transparency efforts.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In April 2016, the company sued the U.S. government, argued that secrecy orders were preventing the company from disclosing warrants to customers in violation of the company's and customers' rights.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On October 23, 2017, Microsoft said it would drop the lawsuit as a result of a policy change by the United States Department of Justice (DoJ).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] In 2022 Microsoft shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Amazon, Google, and Oracle.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] On a Friday afternoon in January 2024, Microsoft disclosed that a Russian state-sponsored group hacked into its corporate systems.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] The group, accessed "a very small percentage" of Microsoft corporate email accounts, which also included members of its senior leadership team and employees in its cybersecurity and legal teams.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p01] Microsoft noted in a blog post that the attack might have been prevented if the accounts in question had enabled multi-factor authentication, a defensive measure which is widely recommended in the industry, including by Microsoft itself.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Technical references for developers and articles for various Microsoft magazines such as *Microsoft Systems Journal* (*MSJ*) are available through the Microsoft Developer Network (MSDN).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] MSDN also offers subscriptions for companies and individuals, and the more expensive subscriptions usually offer access to pre-release beta versions of Microsoft software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In April 2004, Microsoft launched a community site for developers and users, titled Channel 9, that provides a wiki and an Internet forum.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Another community site that provides daily videocasts and other services, On10.net, launched on March 3, 2006.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Free technical support is traditionally provided through online Usenet newsgroups, and CompuServe in the past, monitored by Microsoft employees; there can be several newsgroups for a single product.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Helpful people can be elected by peers or Microsoft employees for Microsoft Most Valuable Professional (MVP) status, which entitles them to a sort of special social status and possibilities for awards and other benefits.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Noted for its internal lexicon, the expression "eating your own dog food" is used to describe the policy of using pre-release and beta versions of products inside Microsoft to test them in "real-world" situations.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] This is usually shortened to just "dog food" and is used as a noun, verb, and adjective.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Another bit of jargon, FYIFV or FYIV ("Fuck You, I'm [Fully] Vested"), is used by an employee to indicate they are financially independent and can avoid work anytime they wish.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft is an outspoken opponent of the cap on H-1B visas, which allows companies in the U.S. to employ certain foreign workers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Bill Gates claims the cap on H1B visas makes it difficult to hire employees for the company, stating "I'd certainly get rid of the H1B cap" in 2005.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Critics of H1B visas argue that relaxing the limits would result in increased unemployment for U.S. citizens due to H1B workers working for lower salaries.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The Human Rights Campaign Corporate Equality Index, a report of how progressive the organization deems company policies towards LGBT employees, rated Microsoft as 87% from 2002 to 2004 and as 100% from 2005 to 2010 after it allowed gender expression.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In August 2018, Microsoft implemented a policy for all companies providing subcontractors to require 12 weeks of paid parental leave to each employee.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] This expands on the former requirement from 2015 requiring 15 days of paid vacation and sick leave each year.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2015, Microsoft established its own parental leave policy to allow 12 weeks off for parental leave with an additional 8 weeks for the parent who gave birth.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2011, Greenpeace released a report rating the top ten big brands in cloud computing on the sources of electricity for their data centers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] At the time, data centers consumed up to 2% of all global electricity, and this amount was projected to increase.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2013, Microsoft agreed to buy power generated by a Texas wind project to power one of its data centers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft is ranked on the 17th place in Greenpeace's *Guide to Greener Electronics* (16th Edition) that ranks 18 electronics manufacturers according to its policies on toxic chemicals, recycling, and climate change.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft's timeline for phasing out brominated flame retardant (BFRs) and phthalates in all products was 2012 but its commitment to phasing out PVC is not clear.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] As of January 2011, it has no products that are completely free from PVC and BFRs.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft makes use of alternative forms of transit.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] It created one of the world's largest private bus systems, the "Connector", to transport people from outside the company; for on-campus transportation, the "Shuttle Connect" uses a large fleet of hybrid cars to save fuel.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The "Connector" does not compete with the public bus system and works with it to provide a cohesive transportation network not just for its employees but also for the public.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft also subsidizes regional public transport, provided by Sound Transit and King County Metro, as an incentive.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In February 2010, however, Microsoft took a stance against adding additional public transport and high-occupancy vehicle (HOV) lanes to the State Route 520 and its floating bridge connecting Redmond to Seattle; the company did not want to delay the construction any further.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft was ranked number 1 in the list of the World's Best Multinational Workplaces by the Great Place to Work Institute in 2011.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In January 2020, the company announced a strategy to take the company carbon negative by 2030 and to remove all carbon that it has emitted since its foundation in 1975.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] On October 9, 2020, Microsoft permanently allowed remote work.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In the same year, it was awarded the EPA's Green Power Leadership Award, citing the company's all-renewable energy use since 2014.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2023 Microsoft consumed 24 TWh of electricity, more than countries such as Iceland, Ghana, the Dominican Republic, or Tunisia.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The corporate headquarters, informally known as the Microsoft Redmond campus, is located at One Microsoft Way in Redmond, Washington.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft initially moved onto the grounds of the campus on February 26, 1986, weeks before the company went public on March 13.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The headquarters has since experienced multiple expansions since its establishment.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] It is estimated to encompass over 8 million ft2 (750,000 m2) of office space and 30,000–40,000 employees.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Additional offices are located in Bellevue and Issaquah, Washington (90,000 employees worldwide).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The company is planning to upgrade its Mountain View, California, campus on a grand scale.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The company has occupied this campus since 1981.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2016, the company bought the 32-acre (13 ha) campus, with plans to renovate and expand it by 25%.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft operates an East Coast headquarters in Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In April 2024, it was announced that Microsoft would be opening a state-of-the-art artificial intelligence 'hub' around Paddington in London, England.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] It was announced that the division would be led by Jordan Hoffman, who previously worked for Deepmind and Inflection.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] On October 26, 2015, the company opened its retail location on Fifth Avenue in New York City.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The location features a five-story glass storefront and is 22,270 square feet.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] As per company executives, Microsoft had been on the lookout for a flagship location since 2009.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The company's retail locations are part of a greater strategy to help build a connection with its consumers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The opening of the store coincided with the launch of the Surface Book and Surface Pro 4.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] On November 12, 2015, Microsoft opened a second flagship store, located in Sydney's Pitt Street Mall.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft adopted the so-called "*Pac-Man* Logo", designed by Scott Baker, on February 26, 1987, with the concept being similar to InFocus Corporation logo that was adapted a year earlier in 1986.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Baker stated "The new logo, in Helvetica italic typeface, has a slash between the *o* and *s* to emphasize the "soft" part of the name and convey motion and speed".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Dave Norris ran an internal joke campaign to save the old logo, which was green, in all uppercase, and featured a fanciful letter *O*, nicknamed the *blibbet*, but it was discarded.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft's logo with the tagline "Your potential.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Our passion."—below the main corporate name—is based on a slogan Microsoft used in 2008.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The new logo also includes four squares with the colors of the then-current Windows logo which have been used to represent Microsoft's four major products: Windows (blue), Office (orange), Xbox (green) and Bing (yellow).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The logo also resembles the opening of one of the commercials for Windows 95.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The company was the official jersey sponsor of Finland's national basketball team at EuroBasket 2015, a major sponsor of the Toyota Gazoo Racing WRT (2017–2020) and a sponsor of the Renault F1 Team (2016–2020).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2025, Microsoft was one of the donors who funded the demolition of the East Wing of the White House and planned building of a ballroom.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2015, Microsoft Philanthropies, an internal charitable organization, was established to bring the benefits of technology and the digital revolution to areas and groups that lack them.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Microsoft's president, Brad Smith, announced that it had donated an initial batch of supplies, including 15,000 protection goggles, infrared thermometers, medical caps, and protective suits, to healthcare workers in Seattle, with further aid to come.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Microsoft began monitoring cyberattacks originating from the Government of Russia and Russia-backed hackers.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In June 2022, Microsoft published the report on Russian cyber attacks and concluded that state-backed Russian hackers "have engaged in "strategic espionage" against governments, think tanks, businesses and aid groups" in 42 countries supporting Kyiv.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft also supports initiatives through its AI for Accessibility grant program, providing funding to various global organizations that create technologies to enhance accessibility for individuals with disabilities.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Among grant recipients from the Asia-Pacific region are the Sri Lankan IT company Fortude, the Thailand-based Vulcan Coalition, and the Indonesian organization Kerjabilitas.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Criticism of Microsoft has followed various aspects of its products and business practices, including surveillance of employees, "Velvet Sweatshop" practices, tax manipulation, and antitrust violations.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Frequently criticized are the ease of use, robustness, and security of the Microsoft's software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The company has also been criticized for the use of permatemp employees (employees employed for years as "temporary", and therefore without medical benefits), the use of forced retention tactics, which means that employees would be sued if they tried to leave.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Historically, Microsoft has also been accused of overworking employees, in many cases, leading to burnout within just a few years of joining the company.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The company is often referred to as a "Velvet Sweatshop", a term which originated in a 1989 *Seattle Times* article, and later became used to describe the company by some of Microsoft's own employees.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] This characterization is derived from the perception that Microsoft provides nearly everything for its employees in a convenient place, but in turn overworks them to a point where it would be bad for their (possibly long-term) health.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] As reported by several news outlets, an Irish subsidiary of Microsoft based in the Republic of Ireland declared £220 bn in profits but paid no corporation tax for the year 2020.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] This is due to the company being tax resident in Bermuda as mentioned in the accounts for 'Microsoft Round Island One, a subsidiary that collects license fees from the use of Microsoft software worldwide.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Dame Margaret Hodge, a Labour MP in the UK said, "It is unsurprising – yet still shocking – that massively wealthy global corporations openly, unashamedly and blatantly refuse to pay tax on the profits they make in the countries where they undertake business".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2020, ProPublica reported that the company had diverted more than $39 billion in U.S. profits to Puerto Rico using a mechanism structured to make it seem as if the company was unprofitable on paper.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] As a result, the company paid a tax rate on those profits of "nearly 0%".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] When the Internal Revenue Service audited these transactions, ProPublica reported that Microsoft aggressively fought back, including successfully lobbying Congress to change the law to make it harder for the agency to conduct audits of large corporations.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2023, Microsoft reported in a securities filing that the U.S.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Internal Revenue Service was alleging that the company owed the U.S. $28.9 billion in past taxes, plus penalties related to mis-allocation of corporate profits over a decade.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] "Embrace, extend, and extinguish" (EEE), also known as "embrace, extend, and exterminate," is a phrase that the U.S.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Department of Justice found that was used internally by Microsoft to describe its strategy for entering product categories involving widely used standards, extending those standards with proprietary capabilities, and then using those differences to strongly disadvantage competitors.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft was the first company to participate in the PRISM surveillance program, according to leaked NSA documents obtained by *The Guardian* and *The Washington Post* in June 2013, and acknowledged by government officials following the leak.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The program authorizes the government to secretly access data of non-US citizens hosted by American companies without a warrant.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft has denied participation in such a program.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In 2020, Salesforce, the manufacturer of the Slack platform, complained to European regulators about Microsoft due to the integration of the Teams service into Office 365.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Negotiations with the European Commission continued until the summer of 2023, but reached an impasse that led to Microsoft facing an antitrust investigation from the European Union.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In June 2024, Microsoft faced a potential EU fine after regulators accused it of abusing market power by bundling its Teams video-conferencing app with its Office 365 and Microsoft 365 software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The European Commission issued a statement of objections, alleging Microsoft's practice since 2019 gave Teams an unfair market advantage and limited interoperability with competing software.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] This action followed a 2019 complaint from Slack, which was later acquired by Salesforce.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft's Teams usage soared during the pandemic, growing from 2 million daily users in 2017 to 300 million in 2023.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The company has a history of antitrust battles in the U.S. and Europe, with over €2 billion in EU fines previously imposed for similar abuses.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In November 2024, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) launched an investigation into Microsoft, focusing on potential antitrust violations related to its cloud computing, AI, and cybersecurity businesses.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The probe scrutinized Microsoft's bundling of cloud services with products like Office and security tools, as well as its growing AI presence through its partnership with OpenAI.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] This inquiry was part of broader efforts by the U.S. government to enforce guidelines on the power of major tech companies.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Concerns were raised about Microsoft's licensing practices potentially locking customers into its services and its AI investments possibly sidestepping regulatory oversight.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft Azure is one of multiple cloud computing services used for data storage by the Israel Defense Forces (IDF).
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The IDF's usage of Azure intensified during the Gaza war and genocide, doubling its stored data to over 13.6 petabytes from March to July 2024.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] According to the complaint and media reports, Microsoft’s cloud services may have been used to store or process surveillance-related data.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The organization requested that European data protection authorities investigate whether this data processing complies with EU law.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In August 2025 a joint investigation by The Guardian, +972 Magazine, and Local Call reported that Microsoft Azure provides storage for mass-surveilled Palestinian phone calls to identify bombing targets in Gaza.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In September, in response to the investigation, Microsoft announced it had ended Azure access for the intelligence-focused Unit 8200 of the IDF.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In June 2025 Microsoft helped suspend the email account of Karim Ahmad Khan, a British International Criminal Court (ICC) prosecutor in the Netherlands who was investigating Israel for war crimes.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Microsoft was complying with a Trump executive order titled "Imposing Sanctions on the International Criminal Court".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] According to The New York Times, Microsoft's rapid compliance with the order, targeting an allied country, concerned European officials, and was seen as a symptom of the worsening relations between the U.S. and EU.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In October 2024, Microsoft fired two employees, software engineer Hossam Nasr and data scientist Abdo Mohamed, who organized an unauthorized vigil at its Redmond headquarters to honor Palestinians killed in the Gaza war.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The employees, part of the group No Azure for Apartheid, sought to address the company's involvement in the Israeli government's use of its technology.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In February 2025, the Associated Press reported that the Israeli military was utilizing Microsoft-developed artificial intelligence tools in its military and intelligence operations against the people of Gaza.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] In May 2025, Microsoft issued an unsigned statement confirming that these services had been made available to Israel, while denying that these tools were employed during the massacre of the people of Gaza.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] On March 20, 2025, before an event at Seattle's Great Hall with Brad Smith and Steve Ballmer, protestors projected "Microsoft powers genocide" on the wall.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] Subsequently, two employees, software engineers Ibtihal Aboussad and Vaniya Agrawal, interrupted AI executive Mustafa Suleyman at a speaking event on April 4, 2025, in protest at the company's support of Israel.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] After the disruptions at these events, Microsoft contacted the FBI in search of assistance in surveilling its pro-Palestinian employees and their allies.
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] The Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions movement added Microsoft to its list of targets for partnering "with the apartheid regime of Israel and its prison system".
[src:azure-overview/microsoft-p02] On August 20, 20 Microsoft employees and their allies were arrested after refusing to disperse from a protest on Microsoft's Redmond, Washington campus.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:azure-overview/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
